{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b125d9bf-eb24-4daa-9d56-4c10cb9c7843","content":"The .NET Android/MAUI workload **bundles its own Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17** and uses it by default. When `JAVA_HOME` points to a different distribution (Temurin), the build tooling can pick up conflicting paths or fail to parse the version string, causing build errors.\n\n**Fix — choose one:**\n\n1. **Let MAUI use its bundled JDK** (recommended):\n   ```bash\n   unset JAVA_HOME\n   ```\n   Remove any `JAVA_HOME` export from your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile` as well.\n\n2. **Or explicitly tell MSBuild which JDK to use** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is safest — it lets each .NET workload version use the JDK it was tested against. If you still need Temurin for other projects, set `JAVA_HOME` only in those project shells rather than globally.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d5a83bcd-3e2e-4be1-8a5a-79b711ceeec5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what common issues exist with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java.\n\nThe most common issue here is that .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI bundles its own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17), but if JAVA_HOME is set to a different JDK, it can cause conflicts.\n\nActually, the more likely issue is about JDK version compatibility. \n\n.NET MAUI with .NET 8 and 9 both require JDK 17, so the Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 should technically be compatible. The problem might be that the Android workload expects to use its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK, and having JAVA_HOME point elsewhere could create conflicts or version mismatches that prevent the build from succeeding.\n\nOn macOS specifically, there's a known issue where Adoptium Temurin installs to a specific path under `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/`, and JAVA_HOME needs to be configured to point to exactly that location for the build system to find it correctly.\n\nBut even when JAVA_HOME is set properly and `java -version` works, .NET 8/9 MAUI Android builds can still fail because the build system internally expects Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and having Temurin set as JAVA_HOME can create conflicts. There's also a documented incompatibility with certain JDK 17 distributions, particularly around version 17.0.12 from Adoptium.\n\nWithout seeing the actual error message, the most common culprits are version mismatches, Gradle daemon issues, or on Apple Silicon Macs, installing the x64 JDK instead of the arm64 version, which causes builds to fail silently.\n\nThe real issue is likely that .NET MAUI bundles its own JDK and uses it by default, so setting `JAVA_HOME` to Temurin might not take effect or could conflict. The solution is either to remove the custom `JAVA_HOME` and let MAUI use its bundled JDK, or explicitly set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file. Alternatively, Temurin 17.0.12 might not be recognized by the Android SDK build tools, even though it's technically JDK 17. The most likely culprit is that MAUI's bundled Microsoft OpenJDK conflicts with the Temurin JDK when JAVA_HOME points to it, causing version parsing or path resolution issues. The fix is either unsetting JAVA_HOME to let MAUI use its own JDK, or explicitly configuring the MSBuild property to point to the correct JDK installation.","outputTokens":1854,"requestId":"3C30:30490E:D1ABE7:1059BF6:6A01293E"},"id":"3121ff79-09b1-4790-aebe-2b74919f3b37","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:57:08.536Z","parentId":"8a14c05a-2089-40ef-af64-06117d2089c5"}
